text.tspan: From research to practice through open-source software

flowRoot.flowPara: The Open Hydrology (OH) project was set up in 2014 as a collaboration platform for open-source hydrological software development.

OH is unique as it brings together researchers and practitioners with a wide range of expertise and interests. OH is an open platform with a website for sharing code (GitHub), publishing documentation, wikis, discussions, and issue/bug reporting.
Open-source software development is a well-known concept but to date not widely applied in hydrological science. What are the benefits?

The linear moments technique was developed by Hosking (1990) to estimate parameters for extreme value probability distributions. This technique is at the core of the Flood Estimation Handbook's (FEH) statistical method to evaluate flood frequency-magnitude curves using recorded annual maximum flow data.

“lmoments3” is a Python programming library for use in academic research (e.g. application to national datasets) or integration into other software. The library is based on original Fortran code developed by Hosking (IBM, 2005) and was originally converted into Python by Gillespie (n.d). OH contributors further optimised the code and integrated this with widely used libraries “numpy” and “scipy”.

OH Auto Statistical is an application to undertake rapid flood frequency-magnitude analyses using the FEH statistical methods. It is a fully open-source package integrating the OH “lmoments3” and “floodestimation” libraries.
- “Enhanced single site” or “pooling group”
- QMED estimation and donor adjustment
- NRFA data download
- Pooling group stations selection
- Frequency curve development
OH Auto Statistical is fully compliant with the FEH and incorporates recent methodology updates (e.g. Kjeldsen et al., 2008; Kjeldsen & Jones, 2009; Kjeldsen et al., 2014).
